  "timeline": [
    "1950: Alan Turing's seminal paper 'Computing Machinery and Intelligence' proposes the Turing Test, a cornerstone of AI philosophy.",
    "1956: The Dartmouth Summer Research Project on Artificial Intelligence officially coins the term 'Artificial Intelligence'.",
    "1960s-1970s: The 'Golden Age' of AI sees the development of early expert systems and problem solvers like ELIZA and SHRDLU.",
    "1980s: The rise of expert systems in commercial applications and the first AI winter due to over-promising and under-delivering.",
    "1997: IBM's Deep Blue defeats world chess champion Garry Kasparov, showcasing symbolic AI's power in constrained domains.",
    "2012: AlexNet's victory in ImageNet marks the breakthrough of deep convolutional neural networks, ushering in the deep learning era.",
    "2016: AlphaGo, a deep reinforcement learning system, defeats Go world champion Lee Sedol, demonstrating AI's mastery in complex strategic games.",
    "2017: The introduction of the Transformer architecture revolutionizes sequence modeling, enabling significant advancements in NLP and other domains.",
    "2020s: Emergence of large language models (LLMs) and generative AI, demonstrating unprecedented capabilities in text, image, and code generation.",
    "Present: Active research into multi-modal AI, ethical AI, and achieving Artificial General Intelligence (AGI)."
